-- Hong Kong shares close down on China, global jitters
-- By Shanghai Newsroom
-- Thu Dec 11, 2014 03:11AM EST
-- None



HONG KONG, Dec 11 (Reuters) - Hong Kong shares finished lower on Thursday weighed down by weakness in both China and overseas markets.

After rallying more than 30 percent in just two weeks, mainland China markets have struggled this week on signs that authorities may be increasingly concerned about speculation in the market. [.SS] Sliding oil prices also continued to take a toll on shares of energy producers, while boosting fuel-sensitive stocks such as airlines. The Hang Seng index <.HSI> fell 0.9 percent, to 23,312.54 points, while the China Enterprises Index <.HSCE> lost 1.0 percent, to 11,255.43 points.Among the most actively traded stocks on Hong Kong's main board were CGN Power Co Ltd. <1816.HK>, up 9.4 percent at HK$3.62  China Jinhai International Group <0139.HK>, up 12.7 percent at HK$0.07 and Bank Of China <3988.HK>, down 1.4 percent at HK$4.10. Chinese investment flowing from Shanghai into Hong Kong through the mutual market access pilot programme took up 0.48 billion yuan of the 10.5 billion yuan ($1.70 billion) daily quota <.SQUOTA.HS>.